SIMPLE: mileage
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mileage
<hw>Mile"age</hw> <pr>(m⟦imac⟧l"⟦asl⟧j; 48)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>An allowance for traveling expenses at a certain rate
per mile.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Aggregate length or distance in miles; esp., the sum
of lengths of tracks or wires of a railroad company, telegraph company,
etc.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>milage</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The number of miles that a vehicle can travel after
consuming a certain quantity of fuel; in the United States, usually
expressed in units of <unit>miles per gallon</unit>; <as>as, smaller
cars tend to get better <ex>mileage</ex></as>. It is sometimes used as a
nmeasure of the energy efficiency of a vehicle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Use, profit or advantage; <as>as, he got a lot of
<ex>mileage</ex> out of one hit record</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Constructive mileage</b></col>, <cd>a mileage allowed for
journeys supposed to be made, but not actually made.</cd>
<rj><au>Bartlett.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mileometer</ent>⟦br⟧
